description: From Middle English selcouth, from Old English selcūþ, seldcūþ (“unusual, unwonted, little known, unfamiliar, novel, rare”), from seld- (“rarely”) + cūþ (“known”); equivalent to seld +‎ couth.

adjectives.description: selcouth (comparative more selcouth, superlative most selcouth)

entries.meaning: (now rare) Strange, unusual, rare; unfamiliar; marvellous, wondrous.
